  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. It is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it enables the integration of illicit funds into the legitimate financial system, facilitating organized crime, corruption, terrorism, and other illegal activities.\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in alignment with international standards and recommendations. Key international frameworks include:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions:** The UN Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) and the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) both include provisions to combat money laundering.\n\n3. **Regional and National Laws:** Many countries have their own AML laws, such as the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States, the Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) in the United Kingdom, and similar legislation in other jurisdictions.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including imprisonment, fines, and asset forfeiture. Financial institutions and other regulated entities are also required to implement robust AML compliance programs to detect and prevent money laundering activities.",
